2.1 Environmental variables

Chlorophyll (Chl) and Mixed Layer Depth (MLD) values for the 2015-2019 period were obtained from the EU-Copernicus Marine Environment Monitoring Service (https://marine.copernicus.eu/)

Products:

  • Chlorophyll GLOBAL_MULTIYEAR_BGC_001_029: cmems_mod_glo_bgc_my_0.25_P1M-M_chl
  • Mixed Layer Depth GLOBAL_MULTIYEAR_ PHY_001_030: cmems_mod_glo_phy_my_0.083deg_P1M-m_mlotst

there is one .nc per variable with monthly data at a 1/12 spatial resolution

#put here the working path where your files have been located

## Chlorophyll
name <-files[1]

2.2 Fishing effort

Spatially explicit estimates of cumulative fishing effort were obtained from Global Fishing Watch (GFW; Kroodsma et al., 2018; accessed in 2024 from the Google Earth Engine: https://developers.google.com/earth-engine/datasets). We summed daily fishing records from trawlers, purse seiners, gillnets, and longliners to obtain spatially explicit totals covering the 20152019 period.

3 Relative abundance of competitors

As a proxy of the relative abundance of the three studied species, a total of 2,534 longline sets from the Spanish longline fleet targeting swordfish and albacore tuna (Thunnus alalunga) along the study area between 2015 and 2019 were included in the analysis (IEO-CSIC database ).

# import data 
sets <- read.table("CPUE/lances_capt_grid.csv", sep = ";", dec = ".", header = T)

# map the sampled longline sets and the density of hooks
sets_sf <- st_as_sf(sets, coords= c("VLONINI","VLATINI"))
st_crs(sets_sf) = 4326

    theme_map

3.1 Standardize the nCPUE

The catch per unit effort (nCPUE) was standardized by applying generalized additive models (GAMs)

  • negative binomial error distribution to account for dispersion in the catch data
  • number of hooks was included as an offset
  • Latitude and longitude were incorporated using a tensor product smooth function to capture spatial variation in catch rates
  • longline type was included as a fixed factor
  • year and boat were treated as random effects to account for variability in sampling effort and fishing efficiency

Separate models were fitted for each species and basin (Mediterranean and Atlantic), resulting in five models, with no model adjusted for mako sharks in the Mediterranean Sea due to an excess of zero catch observations.

# load 
catch <- read.table("CPUE/lances_capt_grid.csv", sep = ";", dec = ".", header = T) %>%
  rename(n_hooks = NUMANZUELOS)

catch[c("year", "month", "palangre", "boat", "gridcell", "FASELUNAR","COESP", "id_lance")] <- lapply(catch[c("ANO", "MES","PALANGRE", "COBARCO", "id", "FASELUNAR", "COESP", "id_lance")], as.factor)

swomed = catch %>% filter(COESP == "SWO" & ANO < 2020 & id != 501)  %>% filter(PALANGRE == 1 | PALANGRE == 3 | PALANGRE == 5) 
swoatl = catch %>% filter(COESP == "SWO" & ANO < 2020 & basin == "atl") 
pgomed = catch %>% filter(COESP == "BSH" & ANO < 2020 & basin == "med") 
pgoatl = catch %>% filter(COESP == "BSH" & ANO < 2020 & basin == "atl") 
iooatl = catch %>% filter(COESP == "SMA" & ANO < 2020 & basin == "atl")

Explore looking for 0s

# Group by species and basin
catch %>%
  group_by(basin, COESP) %>%
  summarize(

fit_swo_med <- gam(n_ind ~ te(VLONINI,VLATINI) + palangre + 
            s(boat, bs = 're') + s(year, month, bs = 're')+
              offset(log(n_hooks)),  
              data = swomed, family = nb())

3.2 Spatial predictions

Create an empty dataframe for each longline type

p1 <- grid  %>%
  mutate(area = ifelse(id > 310, "med", "atl")) %>% 
  filter(id %in% catch$id) %>% 
  mutate(VLONINI = centrdX,
         VLATINI = centrdY,
         palangre = as.factor(1),
         n_hooks = 1000,
         boat = as.factor(0),
         year = as.factor(0),
         month = as.factor(0))

for (i in 2:10){
  dataframe <- p1 %>% mutate(palangre = as.factor(i))
  assign(paste0("p",i), dataframe)
}
  1. Swordfish
# Make predictions without random effects
pred1 <- predict(fit_swo_med, newdata = p1, se.fit = TRUE, type = "response")
pred3 <- predict(fit_swo_med, newdata = p3, se.fit = TRUE, type = "response")
pred5 <- predict(fit_swo_med, newdata = p5, se.fit = TRUE, type = "response")
pred2 <- predict(fit_swo_atl, newdata = p2, se.fit = TRUE, type = "response")

pred <- data.frame(id = p1$id,
                   area = p1$area,
                   p1 = pred1$fit,
                   p3 = pred3$fit,
                   p5 = pred5$fit,
                   sum_atl = pred2$fit)  %>%
        mutate(mean_med = rowMeans(dplyr::select(., starts_with("p"))))  %>%
        summarise(id = id, swo = ifelse(area == "med", mean_med, sum_atl))

grid_ind0 = merge(grid, pred, by  = "id")
